{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513912"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:16:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:16:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12249"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12249"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.05,0.07,0.79,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4771"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78432"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4771"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12249"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63794"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"1950"},{"type":"tags","id":"3496"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7598"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7608"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26768"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34986"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42721"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43309"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78432"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 85-year-old man presents to his general practitioner, concerned about some blistering on his skin, especially in the axilla, trunk and abdomen associated with severe itching for 1 month. They are painless but very itchy. His other health issues include hypertension and cardiac failure. His medications include valsartan and aspirin, with the occasional use of indomethacin for back pain. On examination, his blood pressure is 140/90 mmHg, pulse 88/min and temperature 37.3\u02daC. He has several blisters on the axilla, trunk and abdomen (Image). They are fluid-filled and thick and do not break when rubbed with the thumb. The rest of the skin and oral mucosal examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stevens-Johnson syndrome","Staphylococcus scalded skin syndrome","Pemphigus vulgaris","Bullous pemphigoid","Dermatitis herpetiformis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient presents with intense itchy and painless blisters on the axillae, trunk and abdomen. This presentation is typical for \u003Cstrong\u003EBullous pemphigoid\u003C/strong\u003E. This is a form of immunobullous disorder that involves production of autoantibodies which target protein at dermo-epidermal junction to induce subepidermal blister. The intact dermo-epidermal junction allows the blister to remain intact and firm, and not flaccid as seen in pemphigus. \u00a0It is more prevalent in elderly patients. It can also be triggered by medications including NSAIDs, furosemide, spironolactone, and more.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPemphigus vulgaris\u003C/strong\u003E is also an autoimmune disorder due to the production of autoantibodies against keratinocyte proteins resulting in acantholysis. The patient presents with painful blisters that first appear in the oral cavity and then afterwards can spread to the skin. The blisters in pemphigoid are delicate and easily break after rubbing off the skin. It can be triggered by the use of medications like penicillamine and captopril.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStevens-Johnson syndrome \u003C/strong\u003E(SJS) (\u0026lt;10% of the body) and toxic epidermal necrolysis (TENS) (\u0026gt;30% of the body) comprise each end on a spectrum of the same disease. These patients will have widespread loss of sheets of skin, a positive Nikolsky\u0027s sign, and will be toxic-even critically ill. Most of the cases when a cause is identified evolve as an extreme drug reaction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStaphylococcus scalded skin syndrome (SSSS\u003C/strong\u003E) can mimic SJS/TENS, but the level of blister formation is intraepidermal and hence presents with flaccid / fragile blisters. Patients do not have mucosal involvement which can help distinguish them from SJS/TENS. A biopsy can be helpful to confirm the diagnosis and exclude SJS/TENS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDermatitis herpetiformis\u003C/strong\u003E is described as clusters of excoriated vesicles and erosions, most commonly on extensor surfaces, the back or the buttocks. It is associated with gluten intolerance and coeliac disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Apart from blistering, bullous pemphigoid is an indolent skin condition usually found in older patients.","Bullous pemphigoid is characterised by tense blisters that do not easily rupture, unlike the flaccid blisters seen in pemphigus vulgaris."],"references":["Porro AM, Seque CA, Ferreira MCC, Enokihara MMSES. Pemphigus vulgaris. An Bras Dermatol. 2019 Jul 29;94(3):264-278. doi: 10.1590/abd1806-4841.20199011. PMID: 31365654; PMCID: PMC6668932. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31365654/","Baigrie D, Nookala V. Bullous Pemphigoid. 2023 Mar 2. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30570995. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30570995/","Bernard P, Antonicelli F. Bullous Pemphigoid: A Review of its Diagnosis, Associations and Treatment. Am J Clin Dermatol. 2017 Aug;18(4):513-528. doi: 10.1007/s40257-017-0264-2. PMID: 28247089. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28247089/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63794"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12249"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18357"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18357","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18357"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5896695f-dcc9-44f8-89f0-8a66b22dec84.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5896695f-dcc9-44f8-89f0-8a66b22dec84.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":554,"height":419}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63794","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63794"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T18:38:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-10T18:39:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4771"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78432"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d